      <hedline>
        <hl1>Foreign Language Classes Offer Cultural Insight; How to Test Fluency</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher F Black letter opposes New York State Board of Regents decision to require three years of foreign language study for high school diploma</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State's Board of Regents is mistaking process for product (editorial, Nov. 20). Yes, an educated person should be competent in a second language. But is mandating three years of classes the best way to foster fluency?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>New York State's Board of Regents is mistaking process for product (editorial, Nov. 20). Yes, an educated person should be competent in a second language. But is mandating three years of classes the best way to foster fluency?</p>
        <p>Teachers know the requirement will produce larger classes of less motivated students, and pressure to pass more students who have not learned much. To make bilingualism part of high standards, why not require that students pass an oral exam with a native speaker before graduating, or translate a chapter of a book into English, or compose a play in a foreign language? Some students may need more than three years of classes, while others may meet the standard with no schooling at all.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER  F. BLACK</p>
        <p>Greenwich, Conn., Nov. 20, 1997</p>
        <p>The writer is an education consultant.</p>
      </block>
